\begin_layout Title
Approaches to reducing obesity problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Rising obesity rates and policies to help reduce obesity.
 Study focuses primarily on US and UK where the problem of obesity has been
 a cause of policy concern.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\size small
Obesity as a Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
The discussions of obesity have dominated the media in recent years.
 The popularity of shows like Biggest Loser and Celebrity fit club survives
 on this revived dilemma of health vs taste.
 While there is some evidence of public concern for obesity rising with
 the size of the health-industry, the medical evidence linking obesity with
 illnesses is quite strong as well.
 The overweight are more likely to experience heart disease, stroke, high
 blood pressure, cancers of colon, breast and prostate, and diabetes.
 With more than 60% of UK adults reportedly obese
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GriffithFood"

\end_inset

, obesity is an area of policy concern.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\size small
High-Calorie Substances and Pigouvian taxes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Despite the popularity of BMI in almost all health-screening tests, it has
 come under a lot of criticism.
 Being an aggregate measure, a BMI-based category can mark a healthy individual
 with more than average muscle mass as overweight.
 Despite counting for false positives, the picture of rising obesity that
 appears isn't a particularly comforting one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
A lot of attention has been to the fat content and high-calorie density
 products.
 The combined effect of cheaper food and rising incomes has cause a trend
 of overeating purportedly responsible for obesity
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FinkelsteinFattening"

\end_inset

.
 With the success of Pigouvian taxes in tobacco, one can hope for a prohibitive
 taxes to work for high-calorie foods - but such attempts have largely proven
 futile.
 Elasticities of nutrients consumption being small, a tax-regime that would
 sufficiently bring down the consumption of target-nutrients would need
 to be very high
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "AlemannoEU"

\end_inset

 - a 50% tax on dairy product lowers fat intake by mere 3% 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChouinardBigMoneySmallChange"

\end_inset

.
 In countries with disparities of income, such a tax burden affects poor
 more than the rich and is likely to result in discontent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
If we were to consider a population split across two parameters - physical
 activity and health-conscious, then obesity would rise for a weight-conscious
 and active person if calorie burning falls by more than calorie intake.
 An active person can consumer more fat and would rather spend time cooking
 at home at the cost of physical exercise
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "YanivJunkFood"

\end_inset

.
 Thin subsidies seem to have a worse effect in this model - as they affect
 a weight conscious and inactive person as well 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "YanivJunkFood"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
With a Pigouvian fat-tax as used in Denmark, severe implementation concerns
 arose as well - when consumers chose to shop for fatty items in Germany
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SnowdonDenmark"

\end_inset

.
 The tax does seem to work in tobacco-products - but additional problems
 arise with fatty foods because the definition of fatty items is more unclear
 than tobacco products.
 The effect of substitutes (instead of fatty foods) on obesity is far from
 conclusive
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SnowdonDenmark"

\end_inset

.
 The health policy makers now find that carbohydrates were more the culprit
 for medical health than the previously claimed fatty substances.
 The failure of the tax was because of the discontent expressed by both
 consumers and businesses - but even if Denmark did succeed in the tax,
 a success can hardly be transplanted without consideration of cross-cultural
 factors, moral hazards and the environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Nothing in the price, availability or advertising of food and drink implies
 a systematic bias against 'healthier choices'.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
The medical fact of extraneous fat accumulating in our bodies still holds
 - but reducing fat consumption alone cannot sufficiently address the problem
 of obesity in a population.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\size small
Other Factors responsible for Obesity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Being overweight among children and adolescents could be explained by parents
 being overweight - however this is only a cross-sectional problem - genetics
 then, may sound hardly relevant to the discussion of rising rates of obesity
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RosinSurveys"

\end_inset

 except through the varied factors resulting in rising obesity rates (e.g.
 habit of overeating).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
A factor completely unrelated is the rise of disposable income itself.
 The percentage of going out has increased and the direct control and cooking
 at home become cheaper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
In all over the developed world (particularly the US), higher income and
 increased access to health facilities combined with growth of the pharmaceutica
l industry has made resulted in a significant increase in the average consumptio
n of medical drugs.
 This has had an impact on obesity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
A convincing theory is just the effect of increasing spending on both health-pro
grams and on food.
 Food has become cheaper and the industry has been able to provide meat,
 dairy and alcohol at a price much cheaper (in the CPI basket).
 The health industry has had similar improvements.
 The rise of both has implied more advertising - and thus there the imbalances
 between consumption and - have become wider.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Various changes in the US built environment have promoted sedentary lifestyles
 and less healthful diets.
 Ewing et al.
 (2003) examined the relationship between urban sprawl and physical activity,
 obesity, and common chronic diseases, and found that urbanization increased
 weight.
 Environment seems to improve obesity instances
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "AmarasinghePrevention"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
A higher rate of time preference could reduce investment in exercise and
 increases caloric intake and therefore increases weight.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
The issue with supply side is often ignored in the media.
 Government-issued agricultural subsidies are worsening obesity trends in
 America
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FranckSubsidies,FosterSubsidy"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

