\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Proponents and opponents of government regulation have had .
 At one end of the spectrum we have the health prescription camp - who think
 that penalties and ceilings are necessary while on the other hand with
 is the Nudge proponents who think only encouragement.
 This doesn't work for children
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GriffithFood"

\end_inset

.
 Griffith provide evidence that suggests that shoppers who say they are
 trying to buy healthy foods, trying to manage their cholesterol level or
 trying to give their children a healthy diet do not appear to succeed in
 purchasing a diet that is lower in saturated fat
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GriffithFood"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
One needs to observe that the public concern on obesity might itself have
 to do with the increased interplay between health and obesity industry
 and higher-disposable income.
 The concern for obesity, ironically, might not be a serious health concern.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
More concerning than the consumption itself has been the lack of knowledge
 of what constitutes a bad diet
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GriffithFood"

\end_inset

.
 Framing models point out that the way options are presented matter
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GriffithFood"

\end_inset

.
 This both points to self-control problems and the insufficiency of Piguvian
 taxes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Prohibitive techniques have had limited success.
 Not so much because of their intent - but because the particular problem
 of healthcare isn't suited for prohibition.
 Health is an environment approach - and while health is a clear area of
 market-failures the government intervention is needed at different points
 of impact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Fat tax cannot be recommended on grounds on non-identifiability, discontent,
 moral hazards and the substitutability.
 That a burger is as dangerous as tobacco is not an easy pill to swallow
 for the most disciplined.
 Targeting one ‘bad’ nutrient with a tax may succeed in reducing consumption
 levels of that nutrient, but may have the unintended consequence of increasing
 consumption of another ‘bad’ nutrient if they are negatively correlated
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GriffithFood"

\end_inset

.
 Sin taxes on tobacco affect smokers but fat-taxes would affect everybody
 - which makes their premise particularly unattractive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
One key measure would be to control advertising.
 Prohibiting cigarettes is not enough.
 Creating awareness (achievable through the private sector) is a preferred
 approach (controlling supply).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
In the US, the government has already receded from a parental approach.
 Whereas that may have discouraged an imposition of fat taxes, other geographies
 may permit more paternalism wherever Nudge propositions fail to apply
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size small
Scandinavian countries have tried national diets (e.g.
 NNUD) more enthusiastically.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
